    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3827840769" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3827840769" />
    <a title="Pranav Prabhu" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/109881652-pranav-prabhu"><img alt="Pranav Prabhu" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1624508404p2/109881652.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3827840769?book_show_action=true">Apr 05, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Pranav Prabhu" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Pranav Prabhu" href="/user/show/109881652-pranav-prabhu">Pranav Prabhu</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/109881652-pranav-prabhu?shelf=science-fiction">science-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3827840769" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13957017552465044974"><blockquote>
  <i>“We are as solid as most truly false things are — a dance of particles in space. Only the things no one can touch are true.”</i>
</blockquote><br/><br/>The Citadel of the Autarch is the fourth and final entry in the Book of the New Sun, barring the coda that is Urth of the New Sun, and it does not disappoint. With its strange, haunting scenarios, amazing character development, and a multitude of revelations, this book is tied for my favourite BotNS entry with book 3.<br/><br/>Severian as a character is quite different from the p</span>
  <span id="freeText13957017552465044974" style="display:none"><blockquote>
  <i>“We are as solid as most truly false things are — a dance of particles in space. Only the things no one can touch are true.”</i>
</blockquote><br /><br />The Citadel of the Autarch is the fourth and final entry in the Book of the New Sun, barring the coda that is Urth of the New Sun, and it does not disappoint. With its strange, haunting scenarios, amazing character development, and a multitude of revelations, this book is tied for my favourite BotNS entry with book 3.<br /><br />Severian as a character is quite different from the person we started out following in Shadow of the Torturer, and the changes that happen to him feel natural and organic. He finds himself in many strange situations and meets a variety of interesting people. Certain concepts are explored in a fascinating way, such as a house where each floor represents a different period of time and how that changes both people and the world as a whole. There is also a larger focus on the dying sun and freezing earth. The book also handles the subject of war and its effects on people. These sections I felt were very well written, with Severian experiencing first hand the chaos and futility of war, while also spending time with injured soldiers from both sides.<br /><br />Wolfe has a proclivity for introducing short stories or tales told to Severian by other people in the middle of the story, and this happened four times in the first half of the book, where four different people recited their stories. This got a bit frustrating as it seemed to just slow down the book and make it more confusing, but that was overshadowed by the brilliance of the fourth and final story. It is narrated in a unique style, with one person telling the story and another translating it into an understandable narrative, with the first person being constrained by limited vocabulary and sentences; it was fascinating to read a story that was written in this way, something I have never seen before. <br /><br />This book also provides many explanations for previous mysteries, while also introducing many new questions in the process. One standout example would be the revelation in the epilogue, which completely recontextualizes the whole story from the very beginning, and looking back, it blows my mind at the things that were originally set up that paid off or made sense by the end.<br /><br />I also particularly enjoyed the various scientific technology and ideas explored that are thinly hidden beneath the veil of mysterious magic, such as references to the nature and possibility of existence of theoretical white holes, written in a way that makes sense within the world and characters without appearing overtly scientific, but more mysterious and magical. Overall, this was a wonderful conclusion to Severian's journey (though there is one more book left) with many revelations, ridiculously weird yet logical scenarios, and hauntingly beautiful prose.<br /><b>8.9/10</b></span>
  <a data-text-id="13957017552465044974" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


